15–Deceased","1122–1160":"1122–1160","1045–1087":"1045–1087","1047–1111":"1047–1111","1080":"1080","1099":"1099","1087":"1087","1085":"1085","18 February 1126":"18 February 1126","2 kwietnia 1111 r.":"2 April 1111","1160":"1160","9 czerwca 1087 r.":"9 June 1087","1115":"1115","1126":"1126","1047":"1047","1122":"1122","1111":"1111","1045":"1045","1144":"1144","około 1115 r.":"about 1115","1109":"1109","Chlumec, Ústí nad Labem, Czechia":"Chlumec, Ústí nad Labem, Czechia","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ota","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Apparently a short form of any of the given names ending in these letters, for example,   Fiona   and   Anona  , now well established as an independent given name."],"variants":[]},{"name":"II.","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Wondrous’ or ‘enlightenment’.","2  ♀ ‘Fine jade’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Černý","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Czech and Slovak (<b>Černý</b>): from Czech <i>černý</i> (Slovak <i>čierny</i>) ‘black, dark’, hence a nickname for a black-haired man or someone with a dark complexion. Compare   Cerna  ,   Cherny  , and   Schwarz  .","French: habitational name from either of two places, in Aisne and Essonne, named Cerny, from the Roman personal name <i>Cernus</i>, a short form of <i>Cerenus</i> or <i>Serenus</i> + the suffix <i>-iacus</i>, denoting an estate."],"variants":[{"name":"Cherny","meanings":["19th-century coinage, probably taken from the vocabulary word denoting the fruit (Middle English <i>cheri(e)</i>, from Old French <i>cherise</i>). However, in some cases it is derived from a transferred use of the surname <i>Cherry</i> (to which the naturalist and pioneer photographer  Cherry Kearton  owed his name).  Dickens  used <i>Cherry</i> as a pet form of   Charity  : in <i>Martin Chuzzlewit</i> (  1844 ) Mr Pecksniff 's daughters Charity and Mercy are known as Cherry and Merry. In modern usage it is perhaps in some cases an Anglicization of French   Chérie ."]},{"name":"Cernoch","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Alois, Erwin, Zigmund.","Czech (<b>Černoch</b>): nickname from <i>černoch</i> ‘dark-skinned man’. This surname is also found in eastern Germany (and formerly in Silesia) in the Germanized form <b>Zarnack</b>. Compare   Cerny  ."]},{"name":"Cernosek","meanings":["Czech (<b>Černošek</b>): diminutive of <i>Černoch</i>, a derivative of <i>černý</i> ‘black, dark’ (see   Cerny  )."]},{"name":"Cerney","meanings":["Irish: Carn, a heap of stones, and neać, a personal suffix, meaning quarryman"]},{"name":"Cerna","meanings":["variant of   Charna ."]},{"name":"Cherney","meanings":["Americanized form of Czech and Slovak <b>Černý</b>, Slovak also <b>Čierny</b> (see   Cerny  ), and probably also of Slovenian <b>Černi</b> (see   Cerni  ), all meaning ‘black, dark’ (see also 2 below).","Ukrainian: nickname based on the Russian adjective <i>chërnyy</i> ‘black, dark’, denoting a black-haired or dark-skinned man.","Americanized form of Slovak and Slovenian <b>Černej</b> (see   Cerney   2)."]},{"name":"Chernin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Aron, Isaak, Ophir, Yakov.  Russian Arkadiy, Arkady, Boris, Igor, Lev, Mikhail, Vladimir, Yevgeny.","Jewish (from Belarus): metronymic from the eastern Yiddish female personal name <i>Tsherne</i>, derived from a Slavic adjective meaning ‘black’ (compare below).","Americanized form of Czech <b>Černín</b>, from a derivative of <i>černý</i> ‘black, dark’ (see   Cerny  ), or alternatively a habitational name for someone from Černice or some other place called with this word."]},{"name":"Churney","meanings":["Americanized form of Czech and Slovak <b>Černý</b> (see   Cerny  ) and of its dialect variant <b>Čarný</b>, Polish and Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic)   Czarny  , Slovenian <b>Černi</b> (see   Cerni  ), or some other cognate Slavic name meaning ‘black, dark’ (see   Cherney  , compare   Charney  )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ota II. Černý Přemyslovec Olomoucký was born in 1085, his father, Ota I. Sličný Olomoucký Přemyslovec, was 40 and his mother, Eufémia Arpad, was 39. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Sophia von Berg. He died on 18 February 1126, in Chlumec, Ústí nad Labem, Czechia, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1085–18 February 1126":"1085–18. veebruar 1126","1080–1109":"1080–1109","1080–Female":"1080–Surnud","1085–1126":"1085–1126","1099–1144":"1099–1144","1115–Female":"1115–Surnud","1122–1160":"1122–1160","1045–1087":"1045–1087","1047–1111":"1047–1111","1080":"1080","1099":"1099","1087":"1087","1085":"1085","18 February 1126":"18. veebruar 1126","2 kwietnia 1111 r.":"2. aprill 1111","1160":"1160","9 czerwca 1087 r.":"9. juuni 1087","1115":"1115","1126":"1126","1047":"1047","1122":"1122","1111":"1111","1045":"1045","1144":"1144","około 1115 r.":"umbes 1115","1109":"1109","Chlumec, Ústí nad Labem, Czechia":"Chlumec, Ústí nad Labem, Tšehhi Vabariik"},"fi":{"1085–18 February 1126":"1085–18. helmikuuta 1126","1080–1109":"1080–1109","1080–Female":"1080–Kuollut","1085–1126":"1085–1126","1099–1144":"1099–1144","1115–Female":"1115–Kuollut","1122–1160":"1122–1160","1045–1087":"1045–1087","1047–1111":"1047–1111","1080":"1080","1099":"1099","1087":"1087","1085":"1085","18 February 1126":"18. helmikuuta 1126","2 kwietnia 1111 r.":"2. huhtikuuta 1111","1160":"1160","9 czerwca 1087 r.":"9. kesäkuuta 1087","1115":"1115","1126":"1126","1047":"1047","1122":"1122","1111":"1111","1045":"1045","1144":"1144","około 1115 r.":"noin 1115","1109":"1109","Chlumec, Ústí nad Labem, Czechia":"Chlumec, Ústí nad Labem, Tšekki"},"fr":{"1085–18 February 1126":"1085–18 février 1126","1080–1109":"1080–1109","1080–Female":"1080–Décédée","1085–1126":"1085–1126","1099–1144":"1099–1144","1115–Female":"1115–Décédée","1122–1160":"1122–1160","1045–1087":